, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."],"variants":[{"name":"Margareta","meanings":["From the Latin form of Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>.  See  <b>Margaret</b>   ."]},{"name":"Margaretta","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705197,"age":55,"year":"1455","julianDay":2252488,"title":"Wars of the Roses","description":"Wars of the Roses was a series of English civil wars for control of the throne of England between the royal families House of Lancaster and the House of York. The name of the war was derived as the red rose was the symbol of the Lancastrians and the white rose was the symbol of the Yorks.","url":"https://www.history.com/topics/british-history/wars-of-the-roses","urlTitle":"History - Wars of the Roses","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Margaret DeHolt was born in 1400, in Clayton le Moors, Lancashire, England, her father, William de Holt, was 31 and her mother, Alice Clayton, was 29. She married Richard Rishton about 1430, in Harwood, Lancashire, England. They were the parents of at least 2 sons and 1 daughter."},"et":{"1400–":"1400–Surnud","1400–Female":"1400–Surnud","1410–Male":"1410–Surnud","1395–1470":"1395–1470","1425–1490":"1425–1490","1440–Male":"1440–Surnud","1445–Female":"1445–Surnud","1370–1433":"1370–1433","1372–1439":"1372–1439","1440":"1440","1395":"1395","Abt 1445":"umbes 1445","1372":"1372","1470":"1470","1370":"1370","1490":"1490","1425":"1425","1445":"1445","1400":"1400","1455":"1455","1433":"1433","1410":"1410","Abt 1430":"umbes 1430","Abt 1440":"umbes 1440","1439":"1439","Duckenhalgh, Rishton, Lancashire, England":"Rishton, Lancashire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Rishton, Lancashire, England":"Rishton, Lancashire, England","Rishton Gt. Harwood, Lancashire, England":"Harwood, Lancashire, England","Clayton le Moors, Lancashire, England":"Clayton le Moors, Lancashire, England"},"fi":{"1400–":"1400–Kuollut","1400–Female":"1400–Kuollut","1410–Male":"1410–Kuollut","1395–1470":"1395–1470","1425–1490":"1425–1490","1440–Male":"1440